<section class="guide-hero">
<div class="page-eyebrow">Protocol Guide</div>
<h1>How to reduce<br>chronic inflammation &#8212;<br><em>what the evidence actually shows.</em></h1>
<p class="guide-hero-sub">Chronic low-grade inflammation is one of the most powerful accelerants of biological aging &#8212; driving cardiovascular disease, insulin resistance, neurodegeneration, and cancer risk. This guide covers every evidence-based intervention that measurably reduces it, ranked by effect size.</p>
</section>

<div class="guide-meta">
<div class="guide-meta-item">Updated <span>May 2026</span></div>
<div class="guide-meta-item">Reading time <span>~13 min</span></div>
<div class="guide-meta-item">Affiliate <span>Disclosed</span></div>
</div>

<div class="content-section">
<h2>Why chronic inflammation is the longevity problem</h2>
<p>Inflammation is not inherently harmful. Acute inflammation &#8212; the redness, swelling, and heat that follows an injury or infection &#8212; is a tightly regulated repair process. The problem is chronic, low-grade systemic inflammation: a persistent, smoldering immune activation that never fully resolves. Gerontologists call this &#8220;inflammaging,&#8221; and it is now recognized as a central driver of nearly every major age-related disease.</p>
<p>The mechanisms are interconnected. Visceral fat tissue secretes pro-inflammatory cytokines including <a href="/biomarkers/il-6">IL-6</a> and TNF-alpha. Senescent cells accumulate with age and release a chronic inflammatory signal called the senescence-associated secretory phenotype (SASP). Gut barrier dysfunction allows bacterial endotoxins to enter circulation. Poor sleep prevents overnight inflammatory clearance. Each of these pathways amplifies the others, producing a progressively inflamed internal environment that damages blood vessels, impairs insulin signaling, degrades cognitive function, and accelerates cellular aging.</p>
<p>The clinical marker most associated with this process is <a href="/biomarkers/hscrp">high-sensitivity C-reactive protein (hsCRP)</a>. CRP is produced by the liver in response to IL-6 signaling, making it a reliable downstream readout of systemic inflammatory activity. The key distinction is the test: standard CRP detects values above 10 mg/L, useful for diagnosing acute illness. High-sensitivity CRP detects values below 3 mg/L &#8212; the range relevant to chronic disease risk and longevity optimization. These are different tests, and the standard CRP ordered in most routine panels will miss the chronic inflammation that matters most.</p>
<div class="callout">
<div class="callout-label">The panel problem</div>
<p>Most routine blood panels include standard CRP if anything at all. High-sensitivity CRP &#8212; the marker that actually reveals cardiovascular and longevity risk &#8212; must usually be requested explicitly. If your doctor says your CRP is normal, confirm that hsCRP (not standard CRP) was measured. They are different tests with different clinical significance.</p>
</div>
</div>

<div class="content-section">
<h2>What you actually need to measure</h2>
<p>A meaningful inflammation assessment goes beyond a single marker. The complete picture requires at minimum three values, and four for a comprehensive workup.</p>
<div class="marker-grid">
<div class="marker-cell">
<div class="marker-cell-label">Primary marker</div>
<div class="marker-cell-title">hsCRP</div>
<div class="marker-cell-ranges">Optimal: <span>&lt;1.0 mg/L</span><br>Ideal: <span>&lt;0.5 mg/L</span><br>High risk: <span>&gt;3.0 mg/L</span><br><br>The standard longevity inflammation marker. Can be transiently elevated by illness or intense exercise &#8212; retest if unexpectedly high.</div>
</div>
<div class="marker-cell">
<div class="marker-cell-label">Upstream cytokine</div>
<div class="marker-cell-title">IL-6</div>
<div class="marker-cell-ranges">Optimal: <span>&lt;1.5 pg/mL</span><br>Concern: <span>&gt;3.0 pg/mL</span><br><br>IL-6 drives CRP production and is independently associated with mortality. Rises earlier than CRP and is more sensitive to metabolic inflammation from visceral fat.</div>
</div>
<div class="marker-cell">
<div class="marker-cell-label">Coagulation marker</div>
<div class="marker-cell-title">Fibrinogen</div>
<div class="marker-cell-ranges">Optimal: <span>200&#8211;300 mg/dL</span><br>Concern: <span>&gt;400 mg/dL</span><br><br>An acute phase reactant that rises with inflammation and independently elevates cardiovascular and stroke risk. Responds to the same interventions as hsCRP.</div>
</div>
</div>
<p>The fourth marker worth adding: <a href="/biomarkers/homocysteine">homocysteine</a>. Elevated homocysteine is both a consequence of and a contributor to vascular inflammation &#8212; it damages endothelial cells directly and amplifies inflammatory signaling. It responds specifically to B vitamin optimization (B6, B12, folate), making it a distinct intervention target rather than just a passive readout. Together, these four markers define the inflammatory landscape that drives biological aging.</p>
</div>

<div class="content-section">
<h2>Every intervention ranked by effect size</h2>
<p>Effect sizes are expressed as reductions in hsCRP or other inflammatory markers. Lifestyle interventions produce meaningful, durable reductions when applied consistently. Supplements produce modest independent effects and work best on top of a solid lifestyle foundation.</p>
