<div class="content-section">
<h2>Supplements with meaningful evidence</h2>
<h3>Omega-3s (EPA+DHA) &#8212; the most evidence-backed anti-inflammatory supplement</h3>
<p>At doses of 2 to 4 grams of combined EPA+DHA per day, omega-3 supplementation produces consistent, meaningful reductions in hsCRP, IL-6, and TNF-alpha across multiple meta-analyses. Standard fish oil capsules typically contain 300 to 500mg of EPA+DHA per capsule &#8212; reaching the effective dose requires 4 to 10 capsules per day, or a concentrated omega-3 product. Measure your <a href="/biomarkers/omega-3-index">omega-3 index</a> rather than guessing at dose. The target is an index of 8% or higher.</p>
<h3>Curcumin &#8212; requires the right formulation</h3>
<p>Curcumin is poorly absorbed in standard form. The research showing anti-inflammatory effects uses formulations with piperine (black pepper extract) which increases bioavailability by 2,000%, or phospholipid-complexed or nanoparticle formulations. A standard turmeric capsule without piperine likely has minimal systemic effect. With proper bioavailability enhancement, doses of 500 to 1,000mg produce meaningful reductions in hsCRP and IL-6, particularly in individuals with metabolic syndrome or elevated baseline inflammation.</p>
<h3>Vitamin D &#8212; correct deficiency first</h3>
<p>Vitamin D has well-established anti-inflammatory effects via its role in regulating immune cell function. Vitamin D deficiency (&lt;20 ng/mL) is independently associated with elevated hsCRP. Correction of deficiency &#8212; not supplementation in replete individuals &#8212; is where the anti-inflammatory benefit lies. The longevity-optimized range is 40 to 70 ng/mL (25-OH vitamin D). Test first, then supplement to target.</p>
</div>

<div class="content-section">
