<div class="content-section">
<h2>Frequently asked questions</h2>
<div class="faq-list">
<div class="faq-item">
<div class="faq-question" onclick="toggleFaq(this)">What is the fastest way to lower hsCRP?</div>
<div class="faq-answer">The fastest clinically validated reductions in hsCRP come from addressing root drivers: weight loss in overweight individuals (a 10% reduction in body weight can lower hsCRP by 26% or more), eliminating ultra-processed foods and refined carbohydrates, and increasing omega-3 intake. Omega-3 supplementation at 2 to 4 grams per day can reduce hsCRP by 20 to 35% within 8 to 12 weeks. Statins also reduce hsCRP independently of their lipid effects, but lifestyle changes should come first.</div>
</div>
<div class="faq-item">
<div class="faq-question" onclick="toggleFaq(this)">What hsCRP level should I aim for?</div>
<div class="faq-answer">For longevity optimization, the target is hsCRP below 1.0 mg/L. Below 0.5 mg/L is ideal. Standard reference ranges classify hsCRP above 3.0 mg/L as high cardiovascular risk, but emerging longevity research suggests even levels in the 1.0 to 3.0 mg/L range are associated with accelerated biological aging. A single hsCRP can be transiently elevated by illness, injury, or intense exercise &#8212; always retest if elevated before drawing conclusions. See the <a href="/biomarkers/hscrp">hsCRP biomarker page</a> for a full range breakdown.</div>
</div>
<div class="faq-item">
<div class="faq-question" onclick="toggleFaq(this)">Which foods cause the most inflammation?</div>
<div class="faq-answer">Ultra-processed foods &#8212; seed oils high in omega-6, refined flour, added sugars, emulsifiers &#8212; are the primary dietary drivers of systemic inflammation. A 2023 BMJ meta-analysis found each 10% increase in ultra-processed food intake associated with a 6% increase in all-cause mortality risk, with inflammation as a key mechanism. Trans fats are among the most potent pro-inflammatory dietary compounds. Red meat in isolation shows modest effects &#8212; the processing and preparation method matters more than the meat itself.</div>
</div>
<div class="faq-item">
<div class="faq-question" onclick="toggleFaq(this)">Can exercise lower inflammation?</div>
<div class="faq-answer">Yes, consistently. Regular moderate-intensity exercise reduces baseline hsCRP and IL-6 in clinical trials. A 2019 meta-analysis found exercise training reduced hsCRP by an average of 0.31 mg/L. The mechanism is partly through weight loss and visceral fat reduction, and partly through anti-inflammatory signaling from skeletal muscle contractions (myokines). The caveat: acute intense exercise temporarily increases inflammatory markers &#8212; this is normal and resolves within 24 to 48 hours. Chronic overtraining can raise baseline inflammation.</div>
</div>
<div class="faq-item">
<div class="faq-question" onclick="toggleFaq(this)">Do omega-3s actually reduce inflammation?</div>
<div class="faq-answer">Yes. Omega-3 fatty acids (EPA and DHA) are the best-studied anti-inflammatory supplements. A 2022 meta-analysis of 34 RCTs found omega-3 supplementation significantly reduced hsCRP, IL-6, and TNF-alpha. The effective dose is 2 to 4 grams of combined EPA+DHA per day &#8212; far above the 250 to 500mg in most standard fish oil capsules. Measuring your <a href="/biomarkers/omega-3-index">omega-3 index</a> is more useful than guessing at dose &#8212; an index of 8% or higher is the evidence-backed longevity target.</div>
</div>
<div class="faq-item">
<div class="faq-question" onclick="toggleFaq(this)">Is chronic inflammation the same as autoimmune disease?</div>
<div class="faq-answer">No. Chronic low-grade inflammation (inflammaging) is distinct from autoimmune disease. Inflammaging is a smoldering background elevation in inflammatory markers driven by lifestyle factors &#8212; visceral fat, poor diet, sleep deprivation, chronic stress, gut dysbiosis, and cellular senescence. Autoimmune diseases involve a misdirected immune attack on the body&#8217;s own tissues and produce much higher inflammation. Persistently very high hsCRP above 10 mg/L without an obvious acute cause warrants investigation for an underlying condition, but most people with mildly elevated hsCRP have modifiable lifestyle drivers.</div>
</div>
